China on Thursday congratulated Yoon Suk-yeol on his election as the new South Korean president. Yoon of the main conservative opposition People Power Party garnered 48.56-percent support in the presidential election held on Wednesday, defeating his liberal rival by a narrow margin, the National Election Commission of South Korea announced on Thursday. Speaking at a daily press briefing, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesperson Zhao Lijian hailed China and South Korea as crucial partners who cannot be separated from each other. Noting that this year marks the 30th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic relations between the two neighbors, Zhao said China and South Korea have seen their relations develop rapidly over the decades. That brings tangible benefits to the two countries and the two peoples, and makes positive contributions to regional peace and development, he added. China stands ready to work together with South Korea to take the 30th anniversary as an opportunity to promote the healthy and stable development of bilateral relations for the betterment of the two peoples, Zhao said. Read more: Yoon Suk-yeol elected South Korean president, vows national unity ROK president-elect says open to dialogue with DPRK (Cover: File photo of Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesperson Zhao Lijian. /Chinese Foreign Ministry)